Different Testing Levels 
Introduction
     Testing levels define the different stages at which software testing is performed during the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC). Each level focuses on testing a specific part of the application, starting from small components and moving towards the complete system.
     The main purpose of testing levels is to identify defects early and ensure the software works correctly at every stage of development.

1. Unit Testing
Definition
Unit Testing is the first level of testing where individual components or smallest units of the program are tested separately.
Performed By
    Developers.
    Purpose
To verify that each function or module works correctly.
To check program logic and internal functionality.

Example
Testing a calculator’s addition function independently:
Input: 5 + 3
Expected Output: 8

Characteristics
    Focuses on single module/function.
    Done before integration.
    Mostly automated.

Advantages
Detects bugs early.
Easier debugging.
Improves code quality.

2. Integration Testing
Definition
    Integration Testing checks whether different modules or components of the application work correctly when combined together.

Purpose:
To verify interaction between modules.
To check data flow and communication.

Example
Login module integrated with database:
User enters credentials.
System validates data from database.

Types of Integration Testing
Top-Down Integration
      Testing starts from main module to submodules.
Bottom-Up Integration
       Testing starts from smaller modules upward.
Big Bang Integration
       All modules combined and tested together.

Advantages
Detects interface defects.
Ensures modules work together properly.

3. System Testing
Definition
       System Testing is performed on the complete and fully integrated application to verify that the system meets specified requirements.

Performed By
Testers (QA Team).

Purpose
Validate entire system behavior.
Check functional and non-functional requirements.

Types of System Testing
Functional Testing
Performance Testing
Security Testing
Usability Testing
Compatibility Testing

Example
Testing full online shopping application:
Login → Add product → Payment → Order confirmation.

Advantages
Ensures end-to-end functionality.
Validates real-world usage scenarios.

4. Acceptance Testing
Definition
        Acceptance Testing is the final level of testing conducted to verify whether the software meets business requirements and is ready for release.

Performed By:
Clients, stakeholders, or end users.

Purpose
Confirm software satisfies user needs.
Provide final approval before deployment.

Types of Acceptance Testing
User Acceptance Testing (UAT)
        End users validate system functionality.
Alpha Testing
    Done internally at developer’s site.
Beta Testing
    Done by real users in real environment.

Example
Client tests application to ensure business workflow works correctly before launch.

Advantages
Confirms customer satisfaction.
Reduces production failures.

Testing Levels Flow
Unit Testing
      ↓
Integration Testing
      ↓
System Testing
      ↓
Acceptance Testing

Testing moves from small components → complete system validation.

Different testing levels help ensure software quality by testing the application step-by-step. Each level focuses on different objectives, 
starting from individual modules and ending with user validation. This structured approach helps detect defects early and ensures reliable software delivery.
